{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774459282,"nonce":"3EsH53ZAUW7O38fZZI9TC16Sq50=","message":"**Correction: rotational symmetry, not true translation invariance**\n\nThe center-out task enforces rotational symmetry around the origin, not true translation invariance. The network receives 9 separate input channels: [sisu(1), goal_pos(2), goal_vel(2), fb_pos(2), fb_vel(2)] — absolute coordinates, not error-relative. Translation invariance emerges from the training distribution (all reaches start at origin) but is NOT built into the input representation.\n\nThis is actually preferable for analysis: keeping fb_pos and goal_pos separate allows perturbing one without the other (essential for feedback perturbation analysis), and enables Jacobian decomposition by input channel. The \"wasted capacity\" learning subtraction is trivial for a linear input layer.\n\nThe input representation should NOT be changed to error-relative coordinates. The separate encoding gives strictly more analysis power. True translation invariance can be validated post-hoc by testing on translated reaches.","files":null}]}